<ReportItem port="0" svc_name="general" protocol="tcp" severity="2" pluginID="50686" pluginName="IP Forwarding Enabled" pluginFamily="Firewalls">
<age_of_vuln>730 days +</age_of_vuln>
<cve>CVE-1999-0511</cve>
<cvss3_base_score>6.5</cvss3_base_score>
<cvss3_vector>CVSS:3.0/AV:A/AC:L/PR:L/UI:N/S:C/C:L/I:L/A:L</cvss3_vector>
<cvssV3_impactScore>3.7</cvssV3_impactScore>
<cvss_base_score>5.8</cvss_base_score>
<cvss_score_source>CVE-1999-0511</cvss_score_source>
<cvss_vector>CVSS2#AV:A/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:P/A:P</cvss_vector>
<description>The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable IP forwarding.</description>
<epss_score>0.0596</epss_score>
<exploit_code_maturity>Unproven</exploit_code_maturity>
<fname>ip_forwarding_enabled.nasl</fname>
<plugin_modification_date>2023/10/17</plugin_modification_date>
<plugin_name>IP Forwarding Enabled</plugin_name>
<plugin_publication_date>2010/11/23</plugin_publication_date>
<plugin_type>remote</plugin_type>
<product_coverage>Low</product_coverage>
<risk_factor>Medium</risk_factor>
<script_version>1.16</script_version>
<solution>On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 &gt; /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key &apos;IPEnableRouter&apos; to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.</solution>
<synopsis>The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.</synopsis>
<threat_intensity_last_28>Very Low</threat_intensity_last_28>
<threat_recency>No recorded events</threat_recency>
<threat_sources_last_28>No recorded events</threat_sources_last_28>
<vpr_score>4.0</vpr_score>
<vuln_publication_date>1997/01/01</vuln_publication_date>
